# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aquabike-world-championship
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aquabike-world-championship/2019-aquabike-world-championship] The UIM-ABP **Aquabike World Championship** is a powerboating sports competition.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/2019-aquabike-world-championship] The UIM-ABP Aquabike World Championship is the premier class of jetski racing, founded in 1992.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/2019-aquabike-world-championship] Aquabike jetskis are personal watercraft vehicles purpose-built for racing and modified according to class.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/2019-aquabike-world-championship] The UIM-ABP Aquabike World Championship is organized and promoted by H2O Racing Ltd on behalf of the Union Internationale Motonautique (UIM), the governing body of powerboating and the exclusive entity recognized by the International Olympic Committee (IOC).
[src:aquabike-world-championship/2019-aquabike-world-championship] This term refers to an Aquabike designed to be stood upon and is powered by rear jet propulsion with a completely closed system.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/2019-aquabike-world-championship] Skis, by definition, are the most demanding to ride as they require high fitness levels and great physical strength as well as agility in the legs and arms.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/2019-aquabike-world-championship] According to the different degrees of modifications to the engine and bodywork, this type of Aquabike is used for three different categories: GP1, GP2 and Stock.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/2019-aquabike-world-championship] Another category (GP3) also exists in which younger drivers, between the ages of 11 and 14, compete.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/2019-aquabike-world-championship] Ski bikes are also used in the Freestyle category however this requires further structural changes to the size and motor, allowing the Ski to become considerably shorter in length, lighter in weight and able to perform better at low engine speeds.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/2019-aquabike-world-championship] Ski bikes are currently used in three different disciplines of the UIM-ABP Aquabike World Championship: Closed Circuit, Parallel Slalom and Freestyle.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/2019-aquabike-world-championship] Runabout refers to the largest and most powerful bikes in the Championship.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/2019-aquabike-world-championship] Runabout bikes are designed for driving while seated and feature a saddle (located towards the front) and a rear jet or a completely closed propulsion system.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/2019-aquabike-world-championship] Runabouts are the most common jetski in the world, as they can also be used for recreational purposes.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/2019-aquabike-world-championship] As with Ski bikes, Runabout bikes are used for three different racing categories: GP1, GP2 and Stock, according to the different degrees of modifications to the engine and bodywork.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/2019-aquabike-world-championship] Runabout bikes are used in five different disciplines of the UIM-ABP Aquabike World Championship: Closed Circuit, Offshore, Endurance, Jet Raid and Parallel Slalom.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/2019-aquabike-world-championship] Regulations require that the path does not exceed 1300m in length.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/2019-aquabike-world-championship] The circuit is marked out by different coloured buoys: yellow (right turn) and red (left turn).
[src:aquabike-world-championship/2019-aquabike-world-championship] Riders are required to complete a set number of laps (varies according to racing division) at the end of which, the chequered flag is waved by marshals.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/2019-aquabike-world-championship] These races are held across long distances and require serious consideration to be taken for refuelling as this is usually done on land.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/2019-aquabike-world-championship] The circuit is bordered by large buoys (visible from long distances) or by natural landmarks like coastline, lighthouses, islands, rocks, etc .
[src:aquabike-world-championship/2019-aquabike-world-championship] Endurance races are held on long closed circuits.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/2019-aquabike-world-championship] As endurance races are testing the long-term resistance of a rider and their bike, these races tend to last several hours and are more akin to a marathon as opposed to a sprint.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/2019-aquabike-world-championship] Given the long duration of the race, supplies are required in advance to ensure everything runs smoothly.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/2019-aquabike-world-championship] Runabout bikes are used in endurance races.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/2019-aquabike-world-championship] These races are spread over several stages.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/2019-aquabike-world-championship] Riders are required to travel long distances marked by checkpoints to complete the race.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/2019-aquabike-world-championship] These races are often very time consuming as riders cover one expanse of water, and reach the coast on the other side, where their bike then has to be transported by land to the next race stage.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/2019-aquabike-world-championship] This category is more of a competition than a race.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/2019-aquabike-world-championship] Riders are given a duration of three minutes to perform a rehearsed routine, one at a time.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/2019-aquabike-world-championship] The stunts are evaluated by a team of five expert judges.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/2019-aquabike-world-championship] The evaluation criteria are: quality, quantity and variety.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/2019-aquabike-world-championship] The most common moves are Backflip, Barrel Roll, 360, Superman and Submarine.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/2019-aquabike-world-championship] Safety and security is of paramount importance during all the races and tests.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/2019-aquabike-world-championship] Each member of the rescue team present at all races is required to have a certificate proving their ability to rescue and transport personal watercraft and injured riders.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/2019-aquabike-world-championship] The support of the firefighters and patrol boats is essential as they ensure the immediate action in case of more serious accidents.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/2019-aquabike-world-championship] On the ground, there is a medical team specialised in traumatology who are able to accompany the riders to the closest hospital to the race site.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/2019-aquabike-world-championship] In offshore racing, there is also a helicopter rescue service.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/aerobic-gymnastics-world-championships] The **Aerobic Gymnastics World Championships** are the World Championships for aerobic gymnastics.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/archery-world-cup] The **Archery World Cup** is a competition **outdoor**organized by World Archery, where the archers compete in four stages in four countries and the best eight archers of each category (from 2010, four archers during 2006–09) advance to an additional stage to contest the Archery World Cup Final.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/archery-world-cup] It has received plaudits for its innovative approach to the sport, raising its profile and reach.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/archery-world-cup] From 2013, the World Cup is broadcast live on Eurosport.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/archery-world-cup] It carries sponsorship from Kia and Longines, which supports the annual Longines Prize of Precision for archery, for the "best male and female athletes that master bow and arrow through concentration, balance, accuracy, and skill".
[src:aquabike-world-championship/archery-world-cup] The following venues have hosted stages of the World Cup Final.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/archery-world-cup] The Longines Prize for Precision is awarded to the male and female archers who shoot the most 10s over the course of the competition at the end of the season.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/archery-world-cup] It has been awarded since 2010 and is awarded to compound and recurve archers in alternate years.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/archery-world-cup] Winners receive a trophy, watch and cash prize of 5,000 CHF.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/archery-world-cup] The following table shows the total number of all medals (including stage and finals).
[src:aquabike-world-championship/archery-world-cup] The following table shows the total number of individual medals (including stage and finals).
[src:aquabike-world-championship/archery-world-cup] An **Indoor Archery World Cup** was inaugurated in 2010.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/archery-world-cup] It is played in the off-season (November to February), with fewer stages and the final competed in Las Vegas.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/archery-world-cup] In 2014, the stages were held in Marrakesh, Singapore and Telford.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/archery-world-cup] 2019-2020 Indoor Archery World Series have 6 qualification and one final stage.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/archery-world-cup] After 2018, the World Indoor Archery Championships were discontinued, leaving the Indoor Archery World Series as the premier championship in indoor archery.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/artistic-billiards-world-championship] The **Artistic Billiards World Championship** is a carom billiards tournament in the discipline of artistic billiards, organized by the Confédération International de Billard Artistique.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/artistic-billiards-world-championship] Raymond Steylaerts of Belgium won the tournament six times, more than any other player.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/artistic-billiards-world-championship] The winners have mainly been European, and more commonly Belgian.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] The **Artistic Gymnastics World Championships** are the world championships for artistic gymnastics governed by the Fédération Internationale de Gymnastique (FIG).
[src:aquabike-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] The first edition of the championships was held in 1903, exclusively for male gymnasts.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Since the tenth edition of the tournament, in 1934, women's events are held together with men's events.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] The FIG was founded in 1881 and was originally entitled FEG (Fédération Européenne de Gymnastique), but changed its name in 1921, becoming the Fédération Internationale de Gymnastique (FIG); this name change roughly correlates with the actual naming of the World Championships.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Although the first such games were held in 1903, they were not initially entitled the 'World Championships'.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] The first competition ever actually referred to as a 'World Championships' at the time was a competition held in 1931 that, while referred to in an official FIG publication as the "First Artistic Men's World Championships", often seems to go ignored by various authorities in the sport.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] The championships prior to the 1930s, beginning back in 1903, would eventually be recognized, retroactively, as the World Championships.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Additionally, repeat World All-Around Champion from 1909 and 1913, Marco Torres was also French-Algerian as he was born in Sidi Bel Abbès.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Perhaps the first African delegation was the Egyptian one which offered forth a full male team at the 1950 World Championships in Basel.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] By the time of these World Championships, a total of 60 male athletes from 6 countries and 53 female athletes from 7 countries comprised the competitive field.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] By the 2013 World Championships, the competition had grown to include 264 men from 71 countries and 134 women from 57 countries.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] As of 2023, over fifty editions of the championships have been staged, and over fifty countries have earned medals in artistic gymnastics events.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] The most successful nation, both in gold medal results and total number of medals, is the former Soviet Union (not including medals from its successor states), and China is the second.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] The United States is the third most successful country in gold medal results while Japan is the third in total number of medals.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Since the fall of the Iron Curtain, the traditional powerhouses in men's and women's individual still had expressive results: Russia, Belarus, Ukraine, China, United States, Japan, and Romania.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] The last two decades were marked by increasing results from two emerging powers: Great Britain and Brazil and at the same period a big decrease in results from Belarus, Romania and Ukraine.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] However, this cycle was broken in 2021, when the COVID-19 pandemic led to the 2020 Summer Olympics to be delayed by one year, the edition scheduled for that year was not cancelled.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] While the Games were held between July and August 2021, the World Championships was allocated to the end of the same year.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] † The FIG (now World Gymnastics) in their 125-year anniversary publication, whereas pre-World War I editions of these championships are concerned, credits the teams and athletes from the Bohemian/Czech lands, then part of Austria-Hungary, as belonging to Czechoslovakia.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] †† There seems to be a history of inconsistency from the FIG's publications regarding whether these 1931 games are considered to be a World Championships.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Last updated after Day 7 of the 2025 World Championships.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Early events such as the 1913 and 1911 championships were purely team events without any individual awards, individual scores were only introduced in 1922, with the first all-round individual men's champion being recognised in that year.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Similarly the first women's championship in 1934 only had medals being awarded to teams, not individuals.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Individual "medals" for these events were therefore only recognised retrospectively and weren't awarded at the time.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Similarly, until 1921 FIG was known as the *European* Gymnastics Federation (*FEG*) and its events were not world championships as such.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] This brief biographical treatment was published at least as far back as 14 January 2017 on the official Facebook website of his alma mater in a photograph album, begun on 29 November 2016, containing other such brief biographical treatments of its notable alumni.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Boldface denotes active artistic gymnasts and highest medal count among all artistic gymnasts (including those not included in these tables) per type.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Few non-primary sources state that at the 1938 World Artistic Gymnastics Championships, in Prague, Vlasta Děkanová of Czechoslovakia won 2 or 3 golds on multiple apparatuses.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] The only primary source on the subject, a book officially released by the International Gymnastics Federation containing the results of the World Championships from 1903 to 2005, informs that medals were distributed only in the team all-around event and in the individual all-around event.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Therefore, according to official reports, Děkanová's official number of gold medals is four, two in individual all-round (1934 and 1938) and two in team events (1934 and 1938) - not six or seven.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Only nations with medals in five or more events are listed.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Positions below third place are not taken into account.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Results for Germany and West Germany have been combined.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Only nations with medals in three or more events are listed.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Positions below eighth place are not taken into account.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/artistic-skating-world-championships-p01] The **Artistic Skating World Championships** ('Worlds') is an annual artistic roller skating competition sanctioned by World Skate (previously the International Roller Sports Federation; FIRS) in which elite figure skaters compete for the title of World Champion.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/artistic-skating-world-championships-p01] First held in 1946, the event is regarded the most prestigious of the sport and a world title is considered to be the highest competitive achievement in artistic skating.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/artistic-skating-world-championships-p01] Skaters compete in many different categories such as men's singles, ladies singles, pairs, and junior categories at the World Championships.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/artistic-skating-world-championships-p01] Due to the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine, World Skate banned Russian and Belarusian athletes and officials from its competitions, and will not stage any events in Russia or Belarus in 2022.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] The **Australian Football International Cup** (also known as the **AFL International Cup** or simply the **IC**) was a triennial international tournament in Australian rules football.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] It was the biggest international tournament in the sport that is open to all nations (it is not called a World Cup as Australia does not compete due to the presence of the professional AFL competition and an abundance of semi-professional leagues).
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] More than 26 nations have participated and the competition has expanded into multiple pools and both men and women's divisions.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] At the time of the last tournament in 2017, the sport had a record 170,744 registered players outside Australia (upwards of 23 per cent of total registered players worldwide) growing at a rate of 25 per cent per annum (as compared to an Australian participation growth rate of 10 per cent).
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] The inaugural 2002 tournament was organised by the first world governing body, the International Australian Football Council.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] With the AFL Commission assuming control over the game internationally, since 2005 it has been run by the Australian Football League (AFL)'s game development arm.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] The IC Grand Final of each men's tournament has been held at the Melbourne Cricket Ground as a curtain raiser to an AFL premiership season match.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] Though it is run under the banner of the AFL Commission, the AFL's official Laws of the Game are not used, an Amateurs variation is instead applied, acknowledging the primarily amateur composition of the competition and that players are not paid for participating.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] Although the competition has grown, its status has remained low for more than two decades, and the arrangement has been criticised due to the focus on domestic competition; the AFL's commitment to fund and promote the sport internationally has also been questioned.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] The Commission stated that it would "continue to review its ability" to stage the tournament in future.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] Competition scheduling discourages it as a standalone spectator event with few pool matches played at stadiums; matches are generally played on weekdays during business hours and rarely with access to ticketed admission, allocated seating, or covered areas.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] The event and matches receive very little if any promotion.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] Despite the limited accessibility for spectators some regional matches played on weekends have attracted significant attendances, with the current attendance record of 5,000 at The Showgrounds, Wangaratta.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] Eligibility rules are very strict compared those of other international competitions.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] Generally speaking, players must be citizens of the country they represent and have lived there through roughly middle school and high school ages (when most players usually learn the key skills required).
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] IC criteria ensures that expatriate Australians, Australians with overseas ancestry and those who moved to Australia at a young age are ineligible to compete (with the exception of the short-lived and unsuccessful women's Indigenous & Multicultural (OzIM) composite amateurs team in 2011).
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] These rules, combined with professional contracts and limited pathways for players, typically preclude professional players from participating.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] In addition, there is a per-team cap on players registered with Australian clubs.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] Despite this, since the 2011 competition, the cup has featured a number of AFL-listed internationals and rookies; however, these players had to first negotiate a release from their AFL/AFLW contracts before being nominated and are not paid for their appearances.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] To date, three players have played senior matches at the highest level in both competitions – the amateur IC and professional club competition: Hewago Oea (Papua New Guinea/AFL), Laura Duryea (Ireland/AFLW) and Clara Fitzpatrick (Ireland/AFLW).
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] Likewise, the tournament forms a pathway for international players to the AFL, with numerous players having been rookie-listed by AFL clubs after their performances in the competition.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] When the International Australian Football Council was formed in 1995 one of its aims was to 'establish and promote an official World Cup of Australian Football'.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] At the time it was thought that 2008, being the 150th anniversary of the game, was the appropriate date.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] However, in 1999 a proposal was received from the New Zealand Australian Football League (NZAFL), suggesting that the World Cup be brought forward to 2002.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] This was accepted by the council and, following visits to many countries, IAFC public relations officer Brian Clarke drafted a discussion paper and draft regulations for circulation to the various national bodies.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] An approach was then made to the AFL, asking for their support in staging the event.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] The AFL agreed on the basis that the event was renamed the "International Cup".
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] An organising committee, chaired by Ed Biggs and including AFL and IAFC representatives, was then appointed.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] All matches were played in Melbourne at mainly second tier suburban and Victorian Football League home grounds.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] Ireland defeated Papua New Guinea in the final at the Melbourne Cricket Ground.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] The second cup in 2005 was run by the AFL's Game Development arm, as the IAFC had been dissolved.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] It saw the addition of Spain but the withdrawal of Denmark and Nauru for financial reasons.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] While most of the venues were similar to 2002, it was the first tournament to have matches held outside Melbourne, with the Victorian city of Wangaratta hosting one of the later rounds.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] New Zealand won their first championship.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] The third cup in 2008 saw a record sixteen nations with China, India, Sweden, Finland and a combined Israel-Palestine side (known as the Peres Peace Team) debuting.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] Tonga entered as a seventeenth team, but as they were unable to commit to the full draw they played a series of multicultural exhibition matches against *Team Asia* and *Team Africa*, sides drawn from Melbourne's migrant communities.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] Like the previous cup, the 2008 event had some matches played outside of Melbourne with the western Victorian city of Warrnambool billed as the co-host and other games being held in Geelong and at Royal Park, Melbourne, featured as a primary venue in subsequent Cups.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] Papua New Guinea, which had advanced to the Grand Final in both previous tournaments, won its first title.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] The fourth tournament, the 2011 Australian Football International Cup, was the first to play matches outside of Victoria, with Sydney being billed as co-host.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] Blacktown International Sports Park and suburban grounds hosted some of the early round matches and a historic first international at ANZ Stadium between the USA and South Africa played as a curtain raiser to a Sydney Swans AFL match.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] A record eighteen nations competed, and a women's division was competed for alongside the men's competition for the first time.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] It was the first tournament to feature a side from Australia, the OzIM women's team, composed of amateur indigenous and multicultural players, however the team did not perform well.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] It was also the first tournament to be split into divisions, seeded from an opening round lighting-style format similar to the 2011 NAB Cup.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] The tournament saw the addition of teams from Fiji (who went on to take out Men's Division 2), France and Timor-Leste.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] Tonga, who had previously withdrawn, also competed but Finland and Samoa did not send teams.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] Ireland won the title in both men's and women's divisions.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] The 2014 Australian Football International Cup saw a significant increase in international and media interest.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] The Israel-Palestine combine was no longer represented and Denmark announced a return to its domestic game development policy.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] Indonesia and Pakistan made debuts in their place.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] As in previous tournaments, one of the rounds was played outside of Melbourne, with matches played at suburban grounds in Melbourne along with regional matches at Bendigo, Ballarat and Geelong.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] South Africa, Fiji and France were the standout improvers.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] Papua New Guinea regained their title in the men's, winning their second title in five tries, while Sweden finished top of Division 2.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] Fiji and Tonga debuted in the women's division and the United States and Canada both fielded two women's teams making a record seven teams.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] Canada achieved a historic first ever title in the women's, defeating Ireland at Punt Road Oval.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] The 2017 Australian Football International Cup once again featured eighteen men's teams, including debutante Sri Lanka, reflecting the game's growth in the Indian subcontinent.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] European teams were finding travel difficult, with northern European nations Finland, Denmark and Sweden (Sweden having competed in both the 2016 Europe Championships and also Denmark in the 2016 and 2017 EU Cups) pulling out, though Croatia and Germany made solid debuts.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] For the first time, the men's divisions were determined prior to the tournament instead of preliminary matches.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] Two themed rounds were featured: the School round, where matches were played at Victorian schools, and the Community round, as in 2014 where matches were played at suburban grounds in Melbourne and Geelong.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] Papua New Guinea won back-to-back men's titles, Croatia won a historic first Division 2 title.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] In the women's, Great Britain, Pakistan and the European Crusaders joined a record field of eight teams with no nations fielding more than one team.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] Ireland regained its women's title over Canada at Docklands Stadium in the first women's grand final match played as an AFL curtain raiser.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] The 2020 International Cup was scheduled for 21 July – 8 August in Sunshine Coast, Queensland.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] It was initially postponed until 2021 due to the COVID-19 pandemic before being cancelled altogether in 2021.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] Prior to the tournament several changes had been announced.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] Criteria were made more strict, reducing the number of Australian based players allowed to compete.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] New Zealand announced the planned entry of its first women's team.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] The AFL had, for the first time, announced capping the men's competition to sixteen teams and the women's to eight.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] In August 2021, the AFL announced that the IC would return in 2023 to align with its original three-year schedule but did not announce the host.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] On 22 April 2022, the AFL announced it was postponing the International Cup until 2024 citing "significant investment required from the AFL to host the event".
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] However, on 24 July 2023, the AFL announced that, in lieu of the International Cup, that it would be sponsoring three regional events in 2024: the Trans-Atlantic Cup, the Asia Cup, and the Pacific Cup to be hosted by an international affiliate.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] The AFL gave no indication as to when the International Cup would be resumed, however indicated that these are the only AFL sanctioned international tournaments since 2017 (effectively nullifying the 2019 and 2022 AFL Europe Championship).
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] AFL Canada was announced as host of the Transatlantic Cup to be held at the Humber College Oval at Colonel Samuel Smith Park in Toronto on August 2–11, The Maroochydore Multi Sports Complex on the Sunshine Coast, Queensland was announced as the host of the Pacific Cup on 14–24 November.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] Thanh Long Sports Center in Vietnam would host the Asia Cup at in Ho Chi Minh City from December 6–8 in 2024.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] The AFL announced strict selection criteria, that each player must hold citizenship for the country that they are representing and must have played in from a local competition in that country.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] "W/D" = Withdrew from the tournament without playing a match after officially committing to field a side that year.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] Prior to 2011, all men's teams competed in one division.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] Sorted by winning percentage, with draws counted as half a win, half a loss, and percentage (points for/points against x 100).
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] Table includes finals and has been adjusted to reflect this.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] ^ Table includes finals and has been adjusted to reflect this.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] Since the 2011 Australian Football International Cup the Men's competition has been split into two Divisions, with the format differing from each past edition.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] In 2011 and 2014, the divisional lineup was decided by a preliminary competition that involved all eighteen teams.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] In 2017, the divisions were pre determined prior to the tournament, with ten teams playing in Division 1 and eight playing in Division 2.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] In 2014, Division Two was decided by ladder position.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] As of the cancelled 2020 tournament there is no formal system in place for qualification of participating sides and countries are extended open invitations to send sides.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] The AFL had, for the first time, announced capping the men's competition to sixteen teams and the women's to eight; however no system for qualification has been proposed.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] While there are now established regional tournaments in Europe, Asia and North America performance in these tournaments does formally affect seedings for the International Cup.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] The tournament is geared towards development of the sport outside Australia and as such player eligibility rules are much more strict than those of other international football competitions.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] Generally speaking players must be a citizen of the country they represent and have lived there through roughly middle school and high school ages (so that is usually where they learned to play).
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] IC criteria ensures that expatriate Australians, Australians with overseas ancestry and those who moved to Australia at a young age are ineligible to compete (with the exception of the women's OzIM team, which is composed of indigenous and multicultural Australians).
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] These rules, combined with professional contracts and limited pathways for players typically precludes professional players from participating and players wishing to participate must negotiate their own release from their AFL/AFLW contracts before nominating.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] In addition there is a per team cap on players registered with Australian clubs which countries teams from stacking their teams with talent developed in Australia.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] This limit was initially set to twelve, however with the increasing number of international players participating in Australian competitions and an increasing number of players learning the game outside Australia, this was later reduced to eight.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] The following AFL and AFLW listed international players have previously represented their country at the IC.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] No senior AFL players on contracts have yet been released to play in the International Cup, like most amateur representative competitions, this is primarily due to the risk of injury.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] However clubs will sometimes make exclusions to allow the participation of lower paid rookies, international scholarship players and AFL Women's players in the amateur tournament.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] Tournament best and fairests have been named since 2005.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] In addition, each nation typically nominates their best and fairest player.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] A World (formerly All-International) Team is selected from the best players (similarly to the All-Australian Team selection in the AFL).
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] Prior to 2008, field positions and captaincy positions were not nominated.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] Captaincies have not been nominated since 2014.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] The IC has maintained a low media profile for more than two decades.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] Apart from the Grand Final which is played as a curtain raiser, matches not scheduled for stadiums are free entry and are generally played midday and mid-week prohibiting it as a spectator event, though some regional matches have been played on weekends.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] The 2002 tournament was video recorded and posted on the IAFC website though there were no live broadcasts.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] The United States Australian Football League also provided video coverage and recorded a documentary on its participation.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] The 2005 tournament attracted some coverage from Fox Sports including a Grand Final replay on Fox Sports (Australia) and the Fox Footy Channel, though matches were not broadcast.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] Some community radio and television stations in Victoria also provided limited coverage and *World Footy News* provided score updates.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] The AFL began posting videos of the 2008 tournament on its website along with editorial posts after the matches were played.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] The AFL failed to secure a broadcast partner for the 2011 tournament, instead adding delayed highlights to their online video service.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] For the 2014 tournament the AFL included live streaming for the first time and the tournament attracted media interest from outside Australia.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] For the 2017 tournament the AFL partnered with Internet service YouTube to provide live streaming of the three rounds held at Royal Park and the two Grand Finals.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] The USAFL, AFL Canada, *World Footy News*, and the Eastern Football League provided supplementary coverage of the school and community rounds.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] IC coverage was not included in the AFL's record breaking 2.5 billion broadcasting deal in 2015 or contract negotiations in 2019 for the 2020 extension, though Kayo will stream AFLW matches.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] The inaugural IAFC tournament was held in the game's spiritual home of Melbourne, with some games at suburban stadiums around the city.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] With the AFL headquartered in Melbourne, all events have been hosted in Victoria, Australia with regional matches in Warrnambool (2008), Wangaratta (2005), the exception being matches scheduled for Sydney, New South Wales in 2011.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] The West Australian Football League expressed an interest in bidding for the 2008 cup to go to Perth, Western Australia however the AFL did not open up hosting to bidders and the tournament was held in Victoria instead.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] The cancelled 2020 tournament was the first time in the history of the event that the AFL opened up to bidders as part of a closed bidding process.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] Among newly introduced criteria was that the grounds must meet the AFL's Preferred Facility Guidelines at Regional level to qualify.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] These include requirements for the ground dimensions and surface, staff facilities, lighting and accessibility.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] The guidelines are mainly aimed at providing AFL staff with maximum amenity, there are no requirements for spectator seating, viewing mounds and a covered area under which spectators can stand are deemed sufficient for calculating ground capacity.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] The guidelines, combined with the requirement to have at least two main fields meeting this requirement in close proximity, has significantly raised the barrier to entry for hosting the tournament.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] At the end of 2019, the AFL announced that it had selected the Sunshine Coast bid which would have seen the event hosted outside of Melbourne and Victoria for the first time (not counting the 2011 event which saw some secondary matches played in Western Sydney).
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] As part of the Queensland bid, the Grand Finals would be played at the Brisbane Cricket Ground as a curtain raiser to a Brisbane Lions AFL premiership match.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] Queensland remained the successful bidder when the tournament was postponed until 2021.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] However following the cancellation of the 2020 tournament, no announcement was made as to whether the Queensland bid would be retained.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] On 22 April 2022, the AFL announced it would be continuing discussions with the winning Sunshine Coast bid.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] The AFL (video game series) by Melbourne game developer Wicked Witch Software has featured selectable teams, including player names, from the IC.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] In particular, AFL Evolution and AFL Evolution 2 let players play the entire IC17 tournament, but at AFL-standard stadiums from around Australia.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] The IC has been a development pathway for several players who have been rookie listed or received an international scholarship with professional AFL clubs or clubs from semi-professional competitions throughout Australia.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] The first player to this pathway was Laura Corrigan who made an AFLW debut in 2016 following a 2011 senior appearance for Ireland.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] In 2022, the first male player, Hewago Oea made his debut in the AFL following a 2017 senior appearance for Papua New Guinea.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] IC's potential as a pathway was first promoted by Kevin Sheedy while coaching at the Essendon Football Club, following the 2005 cup he invited Japanese IC players Michito Sakaki and Tsuyoshi Kase to train and play with the club's pre-season team.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] Though Essendon did not recruit Sakaki, he received an invitation to AFL Draft Camp and the exposure was a catalyst for the Wodonga Raiders club contracting him to play semi-professionally in the strong Ovens & Murray league in 2006.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] For older international players, the IC is one of the only options other than moving to Australia and moving up the semi-professional competition pathway, to be noticed by recruiters and rookie listed to the AFL or AFLW.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] Unlike the AFL International Combine open-aged pathway, the IC is accessible to amateurs from a much broader international area and tests their gameplay and game sense, rather than just their athletic attributes.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] For underaged international players the IC provides an alternative pathway and the opportunity to prove their ability to compete at a high senior level.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] Currently only New Zealand competes against the AFL Academy (Australia's best junior players) (though South Africa has in the past).
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] Since the first IC has been a major pathway for Papua New Guineans to play professionally (even with affiliations to Queensland in the National Championships).
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] IC players from other countries to have been recruited to play professionally include Padraig Lucey (Ireland) at Geelong Football Club, Joe Baker-Thomas (New Zealand) at St Kilda Football Club, Yoshi Harris (Nauru) at GWS Giants, and Kendra Heil (Canada) at Collingwood.
[src:aquabike-world-championship/australian-football-international-cup] All of these players were rookie listed shortly following outstanding performances in an IC tournament.
